        "content": "Your daily dose of folic acid is an important way to prepare for a healthy pregnancy. While it can become monotonous taking supplements every day, it is important that you continue with your daily dose of folic acid through your first trimester of pregnancy.\r\n\r\nThere is strong evidence to support the fact that folic acid can reduce the risk of neural tube defects, such as spina bifida and anencephaly, which occur when the spinal cord and\/or the brain do not develop normally.\r\n\r\nThe current recommended daily dose of folic acid is between 500 mcg and 1000 mcg per day. Higher dosages of folic acid may be recommended for women taking certain types of medication, women with diabetes, and those with a familial history of neural tube defect. If you are not sure whether you are taking the correct dose check it with your doctor.\r\n\r\nIn addition to folic acid, many countries are now recommending iodine supplements during pregnancy. Low levels of iodine can lead to an increased risk of miscarriage, premature labor and an increased risk of intellectual impairment. The current recommendation for iodine supplements is 150 mcg per day to be taken before and pregnancy and while breast-feeding. As with folic acid, it is important to discuss the need and dose of any supplements with your doctor to make sure that they do not interact with any other medications you may be on or interfere with any medical conditions you may have.\r\n",
