        "content_type": "Text",
        "content": "You have indicated that you are not menstruating at all. When you do not menstruate at all you are probably not ovulating at all and it is extremely unlikely that you will become pregnant spontaneously. When you do not ovulate at all you are said to be anovulatory. There are a number of reasons why you may not be ovulating. Hormonal imbalances are the most common reason for failure to ovulate and your diagnosis of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) may be a contributing factor.\r\nPCOS is one of the leading causes of infertility in women. Polycystic ovaries occur when the ovaries repeatedly fail to release the eggs from developing follicles. When this occurs the follicles will fail to develop, shrivel up and the remnants will remain located around the surface of the ovaries. The condition is diagnosed on an ultrasound examination and by definition PCO is present if there are 12 or more follicles within at least one ovary. PCOS is diagnosed if there are PCO ultrasound findings and some clinical symptoms including irregular menstruation or symptoms associated with an excess of male hormones (androgens) produced by the ovary. These include obesity, acne, pimples and increased hair growth.\r\n\r\nDuring fertility treatment, womenwith PCOS tend to be very sensitive to follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and will easily over stimulate, making them more susceptible to ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome (OHSS). It is important to note that if you have been shown to have polycystic ovaries it does not necessarily mean you have polycystic ovarian syndrome. You can have polycystic ovaries and not suffer with PCOS. If it is confirmed that you have PCOS and require ovarian stimulation your FSH dose will need to be carefully considered and often reduced to avoid ovarian hyperstimulation. Despite the challenges that PCOS presents, women with PCOS can achieve a safe and successful pregnancy using ART.\r\n\r\nThere is no single test that can diagnose PCOS. However, there are a number of assessments that will assist in confirming whether you have PCOS or not. They include:\r\n\r\nPhysical examination and history. PCOS is often associated with other symptoms including an increased BMI, abnormal hair growth, acne and menstrual irregularities. However, you could have all or none of these symptoms and still suffer with the effects of PCOS.\r\n\r\nA trans-vaginal ultrasound will look at the size and shape of your ovaries in order to identify any abnormalities. The appearance of multiple cysts in an ovary is used to make the diagnosis of PCO. It becomes PCOS if symptoms, described above are associated with the ultrasound findings.\r\n\r\nBlood tests that assess the level of a variety of hormones. These tests commonly include:\r\n\r\nEstradiol\r\nProgesterone\r\nFollicle stimulating hormone (FSH)\r\nLuteinizing hormone (LH)\r\nFree testosterone\r\nProlactin\r\nAnti-mullerian hormone (AMH)\r\nDHEA\r\nSex hormone binding globulin\r\nAn oral glucose tolerance test. This test looks to see if you are insulin resistant. Some women with PCOS are also found to be insulin resistant. This means that the production of insulin needs to be higher to maintain normal blood sugar levels. High levels of insulin can interfere with regular ovulation. Metformin is an oral medication that lowers blood sugar levels countering the affect of high insulin levels and promoting regular ovulation. For some years Metformin was widely used in IVF treatment protocols to restore ovulation, but it has now been shown to be less effective than clomiphene citrate. These days the use of Metformin is restricted to women who are proven to be insulin resistant.\r\nPremature menopause (also known as premature ovarian insufficiency) may be another reason you are failing to menstruate. Premature menopause occurs when your ovary runs out of responsive follicles, a situation which normally occurs at menopause. Elevated FSH levels are used in the diagnosis of premature menopause. Unfortunately there is no treatment for premature menopause and egg or embryo donation using IVF is the best ART option.\r\n\r\nYour low BMI may also be a contributing factor to anovulation. First line treatment for anovulation is to attempt to induce ovulation. Establishing a BMI with normal parameters can help restore ovulation. In the absence of any other identifiable reason for your sub-fertility, treatment may include the use of ovarian stimulating drugs. Fertility treatments specific for anovulation are outlined in Section 5 of this report.",
